observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee, to conduct the three-month physical count to validate the reconciled reports from MGSO and MAO and ensure that all counted items are properly specified and identified detailing physical attributes and location in the RPCPPE;
b. Require the proper disposition as prescribed in the Circular for the missing items, found at station, and beginning balances in the accounting records uncovered in the one-time cleansing;
c. (other recommended actions as per the Audit Report).

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the
a. Municipal Treasurer to:
(i) update the RPTAR/TIC and submit the Certified List of Taxpayers to the Accounting Office;
(ii) prepare the data necessary in the computation of the RPT Target Collections based on the formula provided by the BLGF;
(iii) make representations for the deployment of support staff to assist in the documentation and collection of tax delinquencies;
(iv) recommend for the filing of legal actions against the tax delinquents; and
(v) strategize on how to maximize tax collections; and
b. Municipal Accountant to:
(i) ensure that balances recorded to set up the receivables are based on the updated RPTAR/TIC; and
(ii) initiate the reconciliation of Accounting and MTO records and to affect necessary adjustment, as warranted.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the MTO to:
a. expedite the completion of the physical count and the submission of the corresponding RPCPPE;
b. reconcile the result of the count with accounting records;
c. conduct an investigation on the missing PPEs and take appropriate action on the result;
d. ensure that all PARs are kept and updated regularly;
e. promptly dispose the unserviceable assets in accordance with the prescribed procedures; and
f. consider the option for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the:
a. former Municipal Engineer to explain in writing the deficiencies, omissions and inconsistencies in the projects’ implementation supported with relevant documents;
b. current OIC Municipal Engineer to:
(i) establish a quality control program that would require frequent inspections and testing to ensure achievement of project deliverables;
(ii) ensure adherence by the contractor with the standards stipulated in the contract and pertinent laws and regulations;
(iii) impose liquidated damages on the contractor, as warranted, in accordance with the prescribed procedures; and
(iv) based on evaluation made on the unfinished projects, recommend for appropriate course of action way forward with the end view of promoting the best interest of the government.
We also recommended and the LCE agreed to initiate the blacklisting of the contractor, as warranted, in accordance with GPPB’s Uniform Guidelines for Blacklisting of Manufacturers, Suppliers, Distributors, Contractors, and Consultants. Further, we further advise the said official to conduct an investigation on the possible misuse of government funds that may have been committed in the implementation of the above-mentioned projects.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the:
a. OIC-MDRRMO, in collaboration with MDRRMC, to:
(i) identify and incorporate, under a separate caption, in the LDRRMFIP the PPAs to be charged to the unexpended LDRRMF from previous years; and
(ii) properly and effectively identify DRRM-related PPAs to allow adequate monitoring of implementation and attainment of the expected outcomes within the budget period;
b. Chairman, Bids and Awards Committee and Head, BAC Secretariat to:
(i) ensure that the necessary procurement information or disclosures are timely posted in the PhilGEPS and conspicuous places; and
(ii) submit the requisite procurement documents;
c. LDRRMO timely submit the mandatory LDRRM reports;
d. Head of Human Resource to recommend for the filling of obligatory positions for the Local Risk Reduction and Management Office (LDRRMO); and
e. Municipal Accountant to strengthen her review function on the requisite documentation of procurements.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the: 

(a) Chairman, Bids and Awards Committee to: 

ensure that the necessary procurement information is timely posted in Government Procurement Policy Board (GPPB) portal and PhilGEPS;

utilize the Municipality’s website in the posting of procurement opportunities and information; 

include warranty clause in the Purchase Order and require all suppliers to submit Omnibus Sworn Statement in accordance with Guidelines for Emergency Procurement under Bayanihan to Heal as One Act; and 

(b) Municipal Accountant to follow Section 175, Chapter 6 and Section 208, Chapter 7, Volume 1 of Government Accounting Manual for LGUs with regards to recognition of Inventory Accounts.

We recommended and management concurred that the Local Chief Executive would require

the Municipal Engineer and the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality; 




(ii) render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System; and 


(iii) provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

the Municipal Treasurer to (i) regularly maintain and update the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads; and 



(ii) keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and 

the Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the JEV to record the beginning balance of the local road network and its components, prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card; 


(ii) keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; and 

(iii) prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Municipal Planning Development Officer and Municipal Engineer to

conduct project planning with reasonable approximation and matching of possible risks with appropriate responsive actions; 




include PPAs in the Local Development Project that are technically viable; 

regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions can be introduced at the earliest time possible; and 

the members of the BAC to align the timelines of procurement processes with the targets indicated in the Annual Investment Plan to ensure timely implementation and completion development projects.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

immediately pursue the execution of the contract by requiring the other contracting party to comply with the special conditions of contract particularly with the delivery of its accessories as well as the labor, installation, testing and commissioning thereof;


provide clear explanation/justification on the delay on the operational stage of the generator set;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to compute and impose liquidated damages for late deliveries pursuant to afore-stated provisions in the contract;

instruct the Municipal Engineer to require from their suppliers the issuance of warranty security on all delivered equipment that will cover the entire defect liability period;

terminate or rescind contracts, in whole or in part, if the management has determined the existence of conditions that make project implementation economically, financially or technically impractical and/or unnecessary; and

adopt legal measures if and when the LGU had established the unfulfilled obligations by the supplier on the executed legal contract between parties.

