We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the Heads of Offices of Accounting and Treasury to (i) complete the conduct of physical inventory of PPEs within a set timeline during the ensuing year; (ii) regularly report to the Office of the Mayor the status of the said physical validation and to suggest appropriate action for the concerns encountered in the process; (iii) render  the corresponding RPCPPE; and (iv) settle the disparities between the RPCPPE and the accounting records; 

(b) assign additional staff to handle the maintenance of property cards at the Treasury Office;

(c) require the Disposal Committee to (i) submit to his Office the proposed guidelines and procedures in the disposal of unserviceable properties consistent with those set forth in pertinent COA regulations; and (ii) facilitate disposal of said assets in accordance with the approved guidelines and procedures.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) send the key officials of LCPC to further training on R.A. No. 9344; 

(b) instruct the LCPC in coordination with the concerned LGU offices to (i) prepare a comprehensive plan on child delinquency prevention and attribute budget therefor in amount equivalent to 1% of IRA; and (ii) oversee its proper implementation as provided for under Section 15 of the said law.

We recommended and Management concurred that the Local Chief Executive direct the: 

(a) official concerned in charge of the preparation of LDRRM accomplishment report to indicate therein the corresponding targeted quantitative and qualitative program, project and activity, date of actual implementation, and the actual costs incurred to facilitate determination of efficiency in program implementation and effectiveness of the projects accomplished; 

(b) Human Resources and Management Officer to (i) prioritize the placement of a fulltime MDDRM Officer who will focus on core functions of the MDRRMO and the hiring of the three mandatory staff personnel to handle the administration, training, research and planning, and operations and warning, to provide adequate support to DRRM activities; and (ii) provide necessary interventions to equip personnel of the required competencies necessary to man and run the ERT and, henceforth, constitute the ERT; 

(c) Municipal Planning and Development Officer to fast track and monitor the preparation of the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP), Comprehensive Land-Use Plan (CLUP), and to ensure that disaster risk management activities are integrated therein; and 

(d) Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) for LDRRMF to facilitate monitoring of fund utilization.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

require Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly signed certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible every beginning of the year for recording purposes; 

instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw a JEV to record the RPT/SET receivables based on the certified list from the Office of the City Treasurer and ensure that the recorded receivables are based on actual reference documents;

encourage the involvement of barangay officials in the tax campaign to reach out to a larger area; and 

intensify tax collections thru formulating strategies to improve collection of real property taxes.

We recommended the following courses of actions on which the management agreed to comply:

mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items and locate the missing documents that could shed light to the unreconciled balances between their records; 

strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results;

investigate the causes for the missing/unaccounted PPE items including those not found on site and identify and the persons deemed liable thereof;

identify all unserviceable properties and equipment, keep them on a secure or “bodega” and disperse them within reasonable time;  

continue to prepare and maintain property cards and property ledger cards; and

properly label the properties and equipment owned by the agency showing the details such as the property name, property number, date acquired, acquisition cost and location of the item.

We recommended the following courses of action to address the audit observations noted and management agreed to:

exert effort to locate the titles of the other lands listed in the Summary of Owned Lands provided by the Office of the Assessor, to properly safeguard the interest of the government;

take immediate action to ensure that the immediate registration and titling of the subject parcels of land in the name of the municipality are undertaken;

allocate funds for incidental expenses to be incurred in the consolidation of titles; and

reconcile the records and documents on file between the Offices of Accounting, Treasurer’s and Assessor’s should be done regularly to ascertain that the balance recorded in the books of the LGU is valid and accurate.

We recommended that management :

 exercise strong political will to collect from delinquent customers their respective accounts due them with the local water system;

issue demand letters to defaulting concessionaires stating therein that services will be discontinued unless payment is received within five (5) days from receipt hereof.

